					<strong>Visa and entry</strong>
					<br>
					<br>
					European Union citizens, together with EFTA and SWISS ones, do not require a visa to study or work in Italy for periods up to 90 days. They must however possess a valid ID card or passport. Once in Italy, if they decide to stay more than 3 months, they must comply with the “iscrizione anagrafica” (enrolment to the registry office), which substitutes the previous “carta di soggiorno”. The request must be submitted to the local municipality offices with enclosed the information required by the administration (i.e. Availability of financial resources). 

					Non EU Citizens are required to apply for a study visa before leaving. They should start these procedures in advance of their planned visit to Italy.
					Applications should be made at the nearest Italian Embassy or Consulate. 
					As the procedures are subject to change, it is worthwhile to call the embassy or to check the website of the visa office for information.
					Once they arrive in Italy they must report to the Questura (Police Department) within 8 days of the arrival.
				</p>
